  "prompt": "Can an L2 visa holder work without EAD?",
  "response": "No, an L-2 visa holder **cannot legally work in the United States without obtaining an Employment Authorization Document (EAD)**. Here's a breakdown of the key points related to employment for L-2 visa holders:\n\n### **What is an L-2 Visa?**\n- **L-2 Visa Overview:** The L-2 visa is designated for dependents (spouses and unmarried children under 21) of L-1 visa holders. The L-1 visa itself is for intracompany transferees who work in managerial positions or have specialized knowledge.\n\n### **Employment Authorization for L-2 Visa Holders**\n- **EAD Requirement:** To work in the U.S., L-2 visa holders must apply for and obtain an **Employment Authorization Document (EAD)** from U.S. Citizenship and Immigration Services (USCIS).\n  \n- **Application Process:**\n  1. **Form I-765:** Complete and submit Form I-765, Application for Employment Authorization.\n  2. **Supporting Documents:** Provide necessary documentation, including proof of L-2 status, copy of the L-1 principal's visa, and other required materials.\n  3. **Fees:** Pay the applicable filing fees unless eligible for a fee waiver.\n  4. **Processing Time:** USCIS processing times can vary, so it's advisable to apply as early as possible.\n\n- **Automatic Work Authorization:** Unlike some other visa categories (e.g., certain H-4 visa holders with EAD under specific conditions), L-2 visa holders **do not have automatic work authorization**. The EAD must be explicitly obtained.\n\n### **Benefits of Obtaining an EAD**\n- **Employment Flexibility:** Once the EAD is approved, L-2 visa holders can work for any employer, start their own business, or engage in freelance work without restrictions tied to a specific employer.\n  \n- **Validity:** The EAD is typically valid for the same duration as the L-2 visa and can be renewed as needed, provided the L-1 status remains valid.\n\n### **Recent and Potential Changes**\n- **Legislative Proposals:** There have been discussions and proposals in the past to streamline or automatically grant work authorization to certain dependent visa holders, including L-2. However, as of October 2023, **no such automatic provisions have been enacted**. L-2 holders must still go through the EAD application process.\n\n### **Consequences of Unauthorized Work**\n- **Legal Risks:** Working without proper authorization can jeopardize the visa holder's status and future immigration benefits. It\u2019s crucial to obtain the EAD before commencing any form of employment.\n\n### **Alternative Options**\n- **Changing Visa Status:** In some cases, L-2 holders may explore changing their visa status to one that allows automatic work authorization if they qualify.\n  \n- **Employer Sponsorship:** While not directly applicable to L-2 status, if an L-2 holder seeks employment sponsorship, they might consider transitioning to a work visa category like H-1B, subject to eligibility.\n\n### **Conclusion**\nTo summarize, **L-2 visa holders must obtain an EAD to engage in any form of employment in the United States**. Without this document, working is not permitted and can lead to serious immigration consequences. It's advisable to consult with an immigration attorney or legal expert when navigating the visa and employment authorization processes to ensure compliance with all regulations.",
